tores perpetuate social inequality in a variety of ways. She observes that workers are often assigned to different tasks and functions on the basis of gender and race; that racial dynamics between black staff and white customers can play out in complex and intense ways; that unions can't protect workers from harassment from supervisors or demeaning customers even in the upscale toy store. And she discovers how lessons that adults teach to children about shopping can legitimize economic and social hierarchies. In the end, however, Inside Toyland is not an anticonsumer diatribe. Williams discusses specific changes in labor law and in the organization of the retail industry that can better promote social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClerks (Retail trade)zUnited States. 0aConsumerszUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in employmentzUnited States. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aToy industryzUnited StatesxEmployees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamerican economics.  abehavioral studies.  abox outlet stores.  aclass issues.  aconsumer behavior.  aconsumer culture.  agender issues.  alabor laws.  alow wage jobs.  anational chain stores.  anonfiction.  arace issues.  aracial dynamics.  aretail industry.  aretail work.  ashopping mall culture.  ashopping politics.  asocial hierarchies.  asocial impacts.  asocial inequality.  asocial justice.  asocial sciences.  asociologists.  asociology.  atoy shopping.  atoy stores.  aunion members.  aupscale shops.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024716140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093949340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805